==English==
===Spellings===
*[[endelong]] ''(obsolete)''

===Etymology===
Old English ''[[andlang]]'' ( > ''[[along]]''), re-formed by popular etymology in Middle English as ''[[end]]'' + ''[[long]]''; partly from Old Norse cognate ''[[endlangr]]''.

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/ˈɛndlɒŋ/}}

===Preposition===
'''endlong'''

# [[along|Along]] (as opposed to across), from end to end of.
#*'''Late C14''': Looke what day that '''endelong''' Britayne / Ye remove alle the rokkes, stoon by stoon — Geoffrey Chaucer, ‘The Franklin's Tale’, ''Canterbury Tales''

===Adverb===
{{en-adv}}

# From end to end.

